    "summary": "The Dirty War was a campaign of state terrorism carried out by Argentina's military junta from 1976 to 1983 against suspected political dissidents, leftists, journalists, students, and anyone deemed subversive. The military seized power in a coup on March 24, 1976, overthrowing President Isabel Perón, and immediately launched a systematic program of abduction, torture, and extrajudicial killing. Estimates of victims range from 9,000 to 30,000, referred to as the desaparecidos — the disappeared.\n\nThe junta's methods included secret detention centers, where prisoners were subjected to systematic torture before being executed. Bodies were buried in mass graves or thrown from aircraft into the ocean. The regime operated with the tacit knowledge and periodic support of the United States government, which prioritized Cold War anti-communism over human rights concerns. The disappearances were conducted covertly to avoid accountability, and families were given no information about their relatives' fates.\n\nThe Mothers of the Plaza de Mayo, a group of women whose children had been disappeared, became an iconic symbol of resistance, gathering weekly in the plaza opposite the presidential palace to demand information. Their courageous public protest helped keep international attention on the abuses. After Argentina's defeat in the 1982 Falklands War, the junta collapsed. Trials of junta leaders in the 1980s resulted in landmark convictions, and subsequent revelations of the full scope of the atrocities made Argentina's Dirty War one of the defining cases in international human rights law.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dirty_War",
